# 1.1 Mechanical Components
This section documents the two active mechanical components responsible for every movement Cheese makes: the EV3 Large Motor and the EV3 Medium Motor. Unlike the chassis, which we rebuilt across three versions, or the sensor array, which changed significantly between v2 and v3, our motor configuration remained constant from the first digital model through the current competition build. The large motor, wired to `OUTPUT_B`, drives the rear axle and supplies all propulsion. The medium motor, wired to `OUTPUT_A`, drives the Ackermann linkage and controls the angle of the front wheels. We committed to LEGO motors rather than third-party units for a reason that shaped our entire development timeline: they connect directly to the EV3 brick and are controlled natively through our `ev3dev2` code, which removed the need for external motor drivers, custom wiring harnesses and the calibration work that non-LEGO hardware would have demanded. That single decision cost us nothing in capability and returned weeks of development time that we spent tuning the robot's behavior instead of debugging its electronics, which for a two-person team working against a competition deadline was the difference between a robot that drives and a robot that merely exists.

## Drive Motor — EV3 Large Motor (`OUTPUT_B`)

The large motor is the larger and heavier of the two units and the only source of propulsion on the vehicle. It sits at the rear of the chassis and drives the rear axle through a direct 1:1 connection with no gear reduction, which means the motor alone carries the entire 888.1 g mass of the robot forward and backward across the track with nothing to mechanically multiply its output. Its specifications describe a machine engineered for force rather than velocity: a top speed of 170 RPM, a running torque of 20 N·cm, a stall torque of 40 N·cm, an operating voltage of 9V, and a mass of 76 g. The stall torque is the number that settled this choice, because at 40 N·cm it is exactly double what the medium motor can produce, and propulsion on our robot is fundamentally a torque problem rather than a speed problem. Every single time Cheese begins to move, the motor must simultaneously overcome three forces acting against it: the inertia of a chassis approaching a full kilogram that resists being set in motion, the rolling resistance generated where the tires meet the mat, and the internal friction of the drivetrain itself. A motor optimized for RPM at the expense of torque would stall against that combined load, particularly at the moment of starting, where the demand is highest. The large motor's torque is what breaks the robot cleanly out of a standstill and sustains it through resistance without bogging down partway through a lap.

A second and less obvious property makes this motor suited to the driving role, and it originates in the physical mass of its rotor. Because that rotor is heavier, the motor carries higher rotational inertia, and once the robot is in motion that inertia behaves like a small flywheel: it stores momentum and releases it evenly rather than in bursts. The practical consequence on the track is that when the robot meets a sudden increase in drag, whether from the additional resistance of turning through one of the four corners or from an inconsistency in the surface, the momentum already stored in the spinning rotor carries the vehicle through the disturbance instead of allowing the motor to hesitate or lurch. For a robot whose entire task is to maintain a consistent pace across three laps while a PD controller corrects its line, that evenness of power delivery is not a peripheral benefit but a requirement, because a drivetrain that surges and stalls produces a moving target that no steering controller can tune against. The motor also contains a built-in rotation encoder, and because our drivetrain runs at a true 1:1 ratio, every degree the motor rotor turns corresponds exactly to one degree of wheel rotation with no conversion factor in between. This gives us the ability to translate encoder counts directly into distance traveled, providing the robot with a measurement of its own progress that is entirely independent of the ultrasonic sensors and therefore unaffected by the reflection problems that distance sensors suffer near corners. The motor's considerable bulk, finally, is what fixed its position at the rear and ruled out any alternative: mounting it at the front would have placed it in direct competition for space with the steering assembly, which already occupies the majority of the front section, and would have concentrated a disproportionate share of the robot's mass directly over the steering axle, degrading exactly the part of the vehicle that most depends on being light and responsive.

## Steering Motor — EV3 Medium Motor (`OUTPUT_A`)

The medium motor performs a task that has almost nothing in common with the large motor's. It contributes zero forward motion to the robot; its sole responsibility is driving the Ackermann linkage that determines the angle of the two front wheels. It is smaller, flatter and substantially lighter than the large motor, with a mass of 36 g, less than half. That physical size is not an incidental detail but a load-bearing part of the design, because the front of our chassis is the most crowded region of the entire robot, already occupied by the steering geometry, the linkage arms and the front axle. The medium motor is the only EV3 motor compact enough to fit into that space without displacing something else, and its low mass ensures that the steering mechanism does not sag under the weight of its own actuator, a failure mode that would introduce mechanical play into the linkage and quietly degrade the precision of every turn the robot attempts. Its specifications are close to a mirror image of the large motor's: a higher top speed of 250 RPM against the large motor's 170, but only 8 N·cm of running torque and 12 N·cm of stall torque. We selected it for its speed and its low mass, and the low torque is not a compromise we tolerated but a characteristic that simply never becomes relevant in this application.

The reason speed outweighs force in the steering role comes down to the actual physical demand that steering places on a motor over the course of a run. Steering is not a single slow displacement executed once per corner; it is a rapid, continuous, repetitive task in which the front wheels travel from center to one side, back through center, and out to the opposite side, correcting the robot's line over and over as the PD controller responds to the distance readings coming in from the wall-following sensors. What that task requires above all is a motor capable of starting, stopping and reversing direction with minimal delay, and the medium motor's low rotational inertia delivers precisely that. Its light rotor reverses cleanly, without the lag and overshoot that a heavier rotor would introduce on every individual correction, and since the robot performs those corrections continuously rather than occasionally, a delay of even a fraction of a second compounds into a visibly unstable line. Equally decisive is positional precision. Steering is a matter of absolute position rather than motion: a commanded turn must produce the same physical wheel angle every time it is issued, or the robot's response to its own code becomes unpredictable and impossible to tune. The medium motor's built-in rotation encoder allows us to command an exact angular position and hold it there under braking, which is the mechanical foundation that makes proportional steering and reliable return-to-center possible in the first place. Its low torque never constrains us because the motor is only ever asked to move the lightweight steering linkage and the two front wheels, never the mass of the robot, which means we capture the full benefit of its speed and precision without paying any price for its lack of raw force.

## The Two Motors as a Complementary System

The engineering value of this configuration lies in the pairing rather than in either motor considered alone. We divided the robot's mechanical work along the boundary between force and precision, assigning the large motor to propulsion, where torque and smooth power delivery are the qualities that matter, and the medium motor to steering, where speed and positional accuracy are the qualities that matter. This pairing was selected against two concrete alternatives, and both were rejected for reasons we can state precisely. Running two large motors would have added 40 g of unnecessary mass to the front of the robot and, more damagingly, would have produced steering that is slow and imprecise, because a heavy rotor physically cannot execute the rapid reversals that continuous line correction demands; the robot would overshoot on every correction and oscillate down the straights. Running two medium motors would have delivered excellent steering but left the drivetrain with a stall torque of only 12 N·cm to move an 888.1 g chassis, which invites stalling at every start and under the additional load that cornering imposes. By matching each motor to the physical demands of the specific task it performs, Cheese is able to do two opposing things simultaneously: drive with force and consistency at the rear axle while steering with speed and delicacy at the front.

